Robert I. Eachus (eachus@spectre.mitre.org) wrote:
:    Hmmm...  You are refuting something that I didn't say.  Whether or
: not production of PGP 1.0 infringed on PKP's patents is not at issue.
: You said that Phil IGNORED the RSA patents.  I pointed out that from
: the beginning, whether or not he infringed the patents, Phil has paid
: attention to them, and informed potential PGP users of the patent
: situation.

I used the word 'ignored' to mean ignoring the moral necessity of
obtaining a proper license or litigating away that necessity in a proper
court. Obviously PRZ knew  before 1.0 that a patent issue was involved.


:  > I don't understand. Do I owe Mr Zimmermann an apology because he no
:  > longer infringes on the RSA patent? Because I pointed out what to me
:  > seems to be a remarkably self-serving inconsistency toward intellectual
:  > property? Because Sternlight is also participating in this thread?
:  > What reason do I owe Phil an apology?

:    See above.  It is not a "self-serving inconsistancy" to develop a
: product and struggle to get it out the door.  It is a fact of
: business, in this country and elsewhere, that first you develop a

I own a software business and I believe that most of us would consider
it rather imprudent to develop a product without a reasonable guarantee
of obtaining a needed license. And it would be commercial suicide to
go ahead and infringe anyway without giving the patent holder the
benefit of due process. Not to mention unlawful and immoral. 


:    If RSA, Inc. and PKP had determined that their interests were
: better served by bringing an infringement case, I assume that they
: would have done so.  (Lots of us think they would have lost, but at

They did complain to other companies, who promptly complied without
seeking to overturn the patent. Perhaps Mr Zimmermann is judgement proof?


: PKP consortium.  To convict Phil in absentia of a crime he was never
: formally accused of seems to me to be self-serving in extremis.

I only accuse, not convict.  And how is such an accusation self-serving?

